<paragraph id="A001DF4071E94A51D1B10CD200546321" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">
<taxonomicName id="EA1237B4BFC7B07CA7EABB71AFAF61CF" authorityName="R. L. Chang &amp; X. Y. Zhang" authorityYear="2021" class="Sordariomycetes" family="Ophiostomataceae" genus="Sporothrix" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Sporothrix villosa" order="Ophiostomatales" pageId="0" pageNumber="181" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="villosa">
<emphasis id="74DA5267944335389A0F9D0F49750110" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">Sporothrix villosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is closely related to two fungal isolates recovered from China in CAL tree, and another two isolates recovered from the USA in ITS and BT trees, which were previously identified as 
<taxonomicName id="94CECA741765C58F633967699722454E" genus="S." lsidName="S. abietina" pageId="0" pageNumber="181" rank="species" species="abietina">
<emphasis id="E95DA3828539EB80E6DFF4255FC7B7C3" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">S. cf. abietina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. This taxon is phylogenetically distinct from all other species in the 
<taxonomicName id="C44438CF31A45CA5AB7C69DC72FB787C" genus="S." lsidName="S. gossypina" pageId="0" pageNumber="181" rank="species" species="gossypina">
<emphasis id="EFADC83B417897215742F5E5CBCE996C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">S. gossypina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species complex (Figs 
<figureCitation id="6E7A13433CA94A162D10E030AE0CCA79" captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Maximum likelihood phylogeny of Sporothrix gossypina species complex using complete ITS region. The isolates recovered in this study are highlighted in color and in bold font. ML and MP bootstrap support values ≥ 75 are indicated at the nodes as ML / MP. Bold branches indicate posterior probabilities values ≥ 0.9. T indicates ex-type cultures." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.83.70925.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/598893" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">6</figureCitation>
- 
<figureCitation id="04012A887F2696BAFC41408DAF9D5E0A" captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 8. Maximum likelihood phylogeny of Sporothrix gossypina species complex using partial CAL gene region. The isolates recovered in this study are highlighted in color and in bold font. ML and MP bootstrap support values ≥ 75 are indicated at the nodes as ML / MP. Bold branches indicate posterior probabilities values ≥ 0.9. T indicates ex-type cultures." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.83.70925.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/598895" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">8</figureCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation id="87F75E64651A6D0E4F97649158CD084D" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/s10482-011-9582-1" author="Six, D" journalOrPublisher="Antonie van Leeuwenhoek" pageId="0" pageNumber="181" pagination="231 - 244" refId="B45" refString="Six, D, Beer, ZW, Duong, T, Carroll, A, Wingfield, M, 2011. Fungal associates of the lodgepole pine beetle, Dendroctonus murrayanae. Antonie van Leeuwenhoek 100: 231 - 244, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1007/s10482-011-9582-1" title="Fungal associates of the lodgepole pine beetle, Dendroctonus murrayanae." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/s10482-011-9582-1" volume="100" year="2011">Six et al. (2011)</bibRefCitation>
classified all the isolates from China, Canada, the USA, New Zealand, Korea, and South Africa that were close to the ex-type cultures on the BT tree as 
<taxonomicName id="8E04FB79A08648ED92D2CAF8AA822CEE" genus="S." lsidName="S. abietina" pageId="0" pageNumber="181" rank="species" species="abietina">
<emphasis id="25A82ED0AF3B60922DEA89D92CDF1AF9" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">S. abietina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, these selected isolates did not form a monophyletic clade. Later, in the phylogenies using BT and CAL gene-regions, these isolates of 
<taxonomicName id="72B649E320258CB0AB0924BE1B1D03B1" genus="S." lsidName="S. abietina" pageId="0" pageNumber="181" rank="species" species="abietina">
<emphasis id="0DC7950AC55685A4B5CE2F99DE6ABF73" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">S. abietina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
did not cluster with the ex-type isolates of 
<taxonomicName id="7F2E17E817536905206EAF8F492D82C1" genus="S." lsidName="S. abietina" pageId="0" pageNumber="181" rank="species" species="abietina">
<emphasis id="6DB6592F034C4886575970E42C0D8970" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">S. abietina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Therefore, these isolates were provisionally identified as 
<taxonomicName id="6D39DC331BAD77AD05250877BC3A2B53" genus="S." lsidName="S. abietina" pageId="0" pageNumber="181" rank="species" species="abietina">
<emphasis id="903B54BCA959FB768E443C4279614C11" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">S. cf. abietina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="C9FC03FC90A05C8360B39237045F92CE" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/s10482-014-0286-1" author="Romon, P" journalOrPublisher="Antonie van Leeuwenhoek" pageId="0" pageNumber="181" pagination="1167 - 1184" refId="B42" refString="Romon, P, De Beer, ZW, Fernandez, M, Diez, J, Wingfield, BD, Wingfield, MJ, 2014a. Ophiostomatoid fungi including two new fungal species associated with pine root-feeding beetles in northern Spain. Antonie van Leeuwenhoek 106: 1167 - 1184, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1007/s10482-014-0286-1" title="Ophiostomatoid fungi including two new fungal species associated with pine root-feeding beetles in northern Spain." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/s10482-014-0286-1" volume="106" year="2014 a">
<normalizedToken id="E4402EDBBEA8E238F0BA2BA364F66761" originalValue="Romón">Romon</normalizedToken>
et al. 2014a
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="1A2631CE1566FF145159B1BFABB23EB4" DOI="https://doi.org/10.3852/13-073" author="Romon, P" journalOrPublisher="Mycologia" pageId="0" pageNumber="181" pagination="119 - 132" refId="B43" refString="Romon, P, De Beer, ZW, Zhou, XD, Duong, TA, Wingfield, BD, Wingfield, MJ, 2014b. Multigene phylogenies of Ophiostomataceae associated with Monterey pine bark beetles in Spain reveal three new fungal species. Mycologia 106: 119 - 132, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3852/13-073" title="Multigene phylogenies of Ophiostomataceae associated with Monterey pine bark beetles in Spain reveal three new fungal species." url="https://doi.org/10.3852/13-073" volume="106" year="2014 b">
<normalizedToken id="05F68CD85FF48E61C10B0CD67768A042" originalValue="Romón">Romon</normalizedToken>
et al. 2014b
</bibRefCitation>
). Our phylogenetic analyses indicated that isolates classified as 
<taxonomicName id="A4C1CA34F23E23B3D33A27170F28AEC5" genus="S." lsidName="S. abietina" pageId="0" pageNumber="181" rank="species" species="abietina">
<emphasis id="361EDA48C082582EE5CF3EFF96978FC7" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">S. abietina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="0D299A2819D4280A5C3DFD95B34E5182" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/s10482-011-9582-1" author="Six, D" journalOrPublisher="Antonie van Leeuwenhoek" pageId="0" pageNumber="181" pagination="231 - 244" refId="B45" refString="Six, D, Beer, ZW, Duong, T, Carroll, A, Wingfield, M, 2011. Fungal associates of the lodgepole pine beetle, Dendroctonus murrayanae. Antonie van Leeuwenhoek 100: 231 - 244, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1007/s10482-011-9582-1" title="Fungal associates of the lodgepole pine beetle, Dendroctonus murrayanae." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/s10482-011-9582-1" volume="100" year="2011">Six et al. 2011</bibRefCitation>
) plausibly included several phylogenetic distinct species. In this study, 
<taxonomicName id="5417134A665A4DC4E8BEDA7FC7BEA0B3" authorityName="R. L. Chang &amp; X. Y. Zhang" authorityYear="2021" class="Sordariomycetes" family="Ophiostomataceae" genus="Sporothrix" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Sporothrix villosa" order="Ophiostomatales" pageId="0" pageNumber="181" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="villosa">
<emphasis id="AF542221B5D71E84ADC7AD55ED49F8D3" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">Sporothrix villosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
recovered produced a sporothrix-like asexual morph similar to other species in the complex. Furthermore, the conidia of 
<taxonomicName id="D6EB14544B9DF432A3E2B47D8AF5D3DE" genus="S." lsidName="S. villosa" pageId="0" pageNumber="181" rank="species" species="villosa">
<emphasis id="E9262E5900A4E35C854DF55530824113" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">S. villosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation id="D3CB73BE80F21E75646A0E9DCBB43CBF" captionStart="Figure 13" captionStartId="F13" captionText="Figure 13. Morphological characters of asexual structures of Sporothrix villosa sp. nov. a fourteen-day-old culture on MEA b-e conidiophores and conidia. - Scale bars: 10 μm." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.83.70925.figure13" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/598900" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">13c</figureCitation>
) are smaller than those of 
<taxonomicName id="848017DE8CD87186B6B6994B2B7130AF" genus="S." lsidName="S. abietina" pageId="0" pageNumber="181" rank="species" species="abietina">
<emphasis id="0FD3CE054DE2B773CAD90CDF876DDE0A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">S. abietina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(1.2-4.1 
<normalizedToken id="FE497A3709FEAF49FC1171E679C234D5" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.7-1.4 vs. 4-7.5 
<normalizedToken id="B7561FE92C98A4E63F12525233FBBD21" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1-2 
<normalizedToken id="A309582C02861AF7C3E124BEDE7EF0D0" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
) (
<bibRefCitation id="5EABBA6B3AB74769D69338F9D415B281" author="Marmolejo, J" journalOrPublisher="Sydowia" pageId="0" pageNumber="181" pagination="193 - 199" refId="B33" refString="Marmolejo, J, Butin, H, 1990. New conifer-inhabiting species of Ophiostoma and Ceratocystiopsis (Ascomycetes, Microascales) from Mexico. Sydowia 42: 193 - 199" title="New conifer-inhabiting species of Ophiostoma and Ceratocystiopsis (Ascomycetes, Microascales) from Mexico." volume="42" year="1990">Marmolejo and Butin 1990</bibRefCitation>
). Unlike 
<taxonomicName id="BDAEC6C774C55BBD9800024BC599972A" genus="S." lsidName="S. abietina" pageId="0" pageNumber="181" rank="species" species="abietina">
<emphasis id="D56FD49FCBBCA2807D52EE42C579EC5D" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">S. abietina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="0E436E82AE3F141F1D0DE27C098B6624" genus="S." lsidName="S. villosa" pageId="0" pageNumber="181" rank="species" species="villosa">
<emphasis id="F1BF9C575FF672BE3263D0CD2E7CDB3A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="181">S. villosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can grow slowly at 35 °C.
</paragraph>
